rogen utilisation from amino acids compared to ammonium; and (iv) co-metabolism of nitrogen sources. Finally, we discover that alanine dehydrogenase, is involved in ammonium assimilation in <italic>M. tuberculosis</italic>, in addition to its essential role in alanine utilisation as a nitrogen source. This study represents the first in-depth analysis of nitrogen source utilisation by <italic>M. tuberculosis</italic> and reveals a flexible metabolic network with characteristics that are likely product of evolution in the human host.</p></abstract><kwd-group kwd-group-type="research-organism"><title>Research organism</title><kwd>Other</kwd></kwd-group><funding-group><award-group id="par-1"><funding-source><institution-wrap><institution-id institution-id-type="FundRef">http://dx.doi.org/10.13039/100010269</institution-id><institution>Wellcome</institution></institution-wrap></funding-source><award-id>104785/B/14/Z</award-id><principal-award-recipient><name><surname>Agapova</surname><given-names>Aleksandra</given-names></name><name><surname>Serafini</surname><given-names>Agnese</given-names></name><name><surname>Petridis</surname><given-names>Michael</given-names></name><name><surname>de Carvalho</surname><given-names>Luiz Pedro Sorio</given-names></name></principal-award-recipient></award-group><award-group id="par-2"><funding-source><institution-wrap><institution-id institution-id-type="FundRef">http://dx.doi.org/10.13039/100010269</institution-id><institution>Wellcome</institution></institution-wrap></funding-source><award-id>Francis Crick Institute Core funding (10060)</award-id><principal-award-recipient><name><surname>Hunt</surname><given-names>Debbie M</given-names></name><name><surname>Garza-Garcia</surname><given-names>Acely</given-names></name><name><surname>de Carvalho</surname><given-names>Luiz Pedro Sorio</given-names></name></principal-award-recipient></award-group><award-group id="par-3"><funding-source><institution-wrap><institution-id institution-id-typ